attributes.name: Richardson Hall
attributes.summary: Opened in 1999, Richardson Hall provides the College of Forestry and the Oregon Forest Research Laboratory with a state-of-the-art research and teaching laboratory to continue linking the needs of one of Oregon's key sustainable industries with future developments in forest products, and forestry sciences.  The building displays a number of artworks including Depression Era wood mosaic panels that were originally installed in Forestry's former campus home, Moreland Hall.
attributes.description: Richardson Hall was constructed with help from a gift of Kaye and Ward, her father, Richardson's 1,400 acre tree plantation near Falls City, Oregon. This 100,000 square foot building is home to the Departments of Forest Science, and Wood Science & Engineering.  In addition to classroom, computing and office spaces, Richardson Hall provides unique laboratories, including a Bio-level 3 AHPIS certified containment facility, a steam feed kiln, and a structural testing room that can simulate earthquake and hurricane damage.

attributes.name: Valley Library
attributes.summary:
The Valley Library was remodeled in 1998 and houses more than just books. The library offers resources for: research, archives, special collections, and other media.

Access to the OSU Public Network is done by first registering your device for OSU access. Access requires affiliation with OSU (Students, Faculty, Staff, Emeritus, and Associates).
attributes.description: The Valley Library provides learning and research opportunities and support for faculty, staff and students through more than 1.4 million volumes and 500,000 maps and government documents. Special collections include the papers of Linus and Ava Helen Pauling and Bernard Malamud, as well as the remarkable History of Atomic Energy collection. As you wander the halls of the library, you'll see the world's largest collection of Pacific Northwest art adorning the walls.

The campus bookstore is 50,000 sq. ft. and retails course materials, academic supplies, technology products and the largest selection of Beaver gear anywhere. It is open to the public, with over 100 customer spaces on the 3rd level of the adjacent parking garage. Revenues from Beaver merchandise subsidize textbooks, saving students over $1 million annually.
